{"title_page": "Landsec", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox company\n|  name   = Landsec \n|  logo   = Landsec logo.svg\n|  logo_size = 150px\n| type  = [[Public limited company]]\n|  traded_as      = {{lse|LAND}}<br>[[FTSE 100 Index|FTSE 100 Component]]\n|  key_people     = {{ubl|{{wd-chairperson}}|{{wd-ceo}}}}\n|  industry       = [[Property]]  \n|  products       = Property Development, Property Investment\n|  revenue        = \u00a3748 million (2019)<ref name=prelims>{{cite web|title=Annual Results 2019|url=https://landsec.com/sites/default/files/2019-05/31%20March%202019%20Prelim%20-%20FINAL_0.pdf|publisher=Landsec|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n|operating_income = \u00a3521&nbsp;million (2019)<ref name=\"prelims\" />\n|net_income       = \u00a3119&nbsp;million (2019)<ref name=\"prelims\" />\n|  num_employees  = \n| company_slogan  =  \n|  foundation     =  {{start date and age|1944}}\n|  location       = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]] \n|homepage         = [http://landsec.com landsec.com]\n}}\n\n'''Land Securities Group plc''' is the largest commercial property development and [[investment company]] in the UK. The firm switched to Real Estate Investment Trust status when REITs were introduced in the United Kingdom in January 2007. It is headquartered in London and traded on the [[London Stock Exchange]], and is a constituent of the [[FTSE 100 Index]].<ref>[http://www.landsecurities.com/about-us/company-overview \"Company overview\"]</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Group traces its origins to 1944, when its founder [[Harold Samuel, Baron Samuel of Wych Cross|Harold Samuel]] purchased Land Securities Investment Trust Limited, which owned three houses in [[Kensington]] and some government stock.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.landsecurities.com/about-us/the-land-securities-story|title=The Land Securities story - Land Securities|work=landsecurities.com|accessdate=16 March 2015}}</ref> Further acquisitions followed shortly afterwards and from 1947 the company concentrated on commercial property.<ref name=\"auto\"/> In the early days some non-UK investments were acquired, but in 1971 these were sold off and the company has concentrated solely on the UK market since then.<ref name=\"auto\"/> The company name was changed to Land Securities plc in 1982.<ref name=\"auto\"/> After buying [[Telereal Trillium|Trillium]] in 2000,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/4471079/Land-Securities-agrees-to-buy-Trillium.html |title=Land Securities agrees to buy Trillium|publisher= Daily Telegraph|date=3 November 2000|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref> it formed a 50/50 JV company [[Telereal Trillium|Telereal]] in 2002 with William Pears Group (WPG) to buy the property portfolio of [[British Telecom]]:<ref>[http://www.telephonehouse.org.uk/telephonehouse/telerealprofile.html BT selects Land Securities Trillium as preferred bidder for property portfolio] BT Group, 10 April 2001</ref>  after selling its shares in Telereal to WPG in 2007, Land Securities sold Trillium to WPG in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/constructionandproperty/4177423/Land-Securities-defends-750m-Trillium-sale.html|title=Land Securities defends \u00a3750m Trillium sale|publisher= Daily Telegraph|date=8 January 2009|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 31 March 2012, Francis Salway was succeeded as chief executive by [[Robert Noel (businessman)|Robert Noel]]. Noel was managing director of the company's London properties, having joined Land Securities in January 2010 from [[Great Portland Estates]] plc, where he had been property director since 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-24/land-securities-ceo-francis-salway-to-step-down-and-be-replaced-by-noel.html| title=Land Securities CEO Salway Is to Step Down for London Manager Robert Noel|publisher=Bloomberg |date=24 January 2012|accessdate=12 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 June 2017, Land Securities rebranded as Landsec. The registered company name remains Land Securities Group PLC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://landsec.com/experiences/future-trends/landsec/land-securities-meet-landsec|title=Land Securities, meet Landsec {{!}} Landsec|website=landsec.com|language=en|access-date=2017-06-23}}</ref>\n\nRobert Noel stepped down as CEO on 31 March 2020. [https://landsec.com/about/management-team/martin-greenslade Martin Greenslade], the company's chief financial officer, acted interim CEO until 14 April 2020. [https://landsec.com/media/press-releases/2020/ceo-appointment Mark Allan] joined Landsec as CEO on 14 April 2020. \n\n==Operations==\n[[File:Cardinal Place - geograph.org.uk - 965776.jpg|thumb|Cardinal Place, a development completed by Landsec in 2006|alt=100 Victoria Street, Cardinal Place photo]]\nLandsec owns and manages more than {{convert|24000000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} of commercial property, from London offices and high street shops to major shopping centres and out-of-town retail parks. At 31 March 2019 the company's property portfolio was valued at \u00a313.5 billion.<ref name=\"prelims\" /> The company owns the [[Piccadilly Circus#Illuminated signs|Piccadilly Lights]] in [[Piccadilly Circus]] in [[London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/constructionandproperty/8796119/Hyundai-in-lights-at-Londons-Piccadilly-Circus.html |title=Hyundai in lights at London\u2019s Piccadilly Circus|publisher= Daily Telegraph|date=29 September 2011|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref> It has also led Project Nova, the development of the area around [[London Victoria station]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.homesandproperty.co.uk/property-news/buying/new-homes/victorias-2billion-transformation-as-its-coach-station-becomes-a-cultural-quarter-with-homes-shops-29715.html|title=Victoria's \u00a32-billion transformation as its coach station becomes a cultural quarter with homes, shops and arts venues|publisher=Evening Standard|date=20 August 2013|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.landsec.com Official site]\n*[http://uk.finance.yahoo.com/q/pr?s=LAND.L Yahoo profile]\n\n{{Portal|Companies}}\n\n{{Land Securities}}\n{{Real estate in the United Kingdom}}\n{{FTSE 100 Index constituents}}\n[[Category:Real estate investment trusts of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the London Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Property companies based in London]]\n[[Category:British companies established in 1944]]\n[[Category:1944 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox company\n|  name   = Landsec \n|  logo   = Landsec logo.svg\n|  logo_size = 150px\n| type  = [[Public limited company]]\n|  traded_as      = {{lse|LAND}}<br>[[FTSE 100 Index|FTSE 100 Component]]\n|  key_people     = {{ubl|{{wd-chairperson}}|{{wd-ceo}}}}\n|  industry       = [[Property]]  \n|  products       = Property Development, Property Investment\n|  revenue        = \u00a3748 million (2019)<ref name=prelims>{{cite web|title=Annual Results 2019|url=https://landsec.com/sites/default/files/2019-05/31%20March%202019%20Prelim%20-%20FINAL_0.pdf|publisher=Landsec|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n|operating_income = \u00a3521&nbsp;million (2019)<ref name=\"prelims\" />\n|net_income       = \u00a3119&nbsp;million (2019)<ref name=\"prelims\" />\n|  num_employees  = \n| company_slogan  =  \n|  foundation     =  {{start date and age|1944}}\n|  location       = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]] \n|homepage         = [http://landsec.com landsec.com]\n}}\n\n'''Land Securities Group plc''' is the largest commercial property development and [[investment company]] in the UK. The firm switched to Real Estate Investment Trust status when REITs were introduced in the United Kingdom in January 2007. It is headquartered in London and traded on the [[London Stock Exchange]], and is a constituent of the [[FTSE 100 Index]].<ref>[http://www.landsecurities.com/about-us/company-overview \"Company overview\"]</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Group traces its origins to 1944, when its founder [[Harold Samuel, Baron Samuel of Wych Cross|Harold Samuel]] purchased Land Securities Investment Trust Limited, which owned three houses in [[Kensington]] and some government stock.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.landsecurities.com/about-us/the-land-securities-story|title=The Land Securities story - Land Securities|work=landsecurities.com|accessdate=16 March 2015}}</ref> Further acquisitions followed shortly afterwards and from 1947 the company concentrated on commercial property.<ref name=\"auto\"/> In the early days some non-UK investments were acquired, but in 1971 these were sold off and the company has concentrated solely on the UK market since then.<ref name=\"auto\"/> The company name was changed to Land Securities plc in 1982.<ref name=\"auto\"/> After buying [[Telereal Trillium|Trillium]] in 2000,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/4471079/Land-Securities-agrees-to-buy-Trillium.html |title=Land Securities agrees to buy Trillium|publisher= Daily Telegraph|date=3 November 2000|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref> it formed a 50/50 JV company [[Telereal Trillium|Telereal]] in 2002 with William Pears Group (WPG) to buy the property portfolio of [[British Telecom]]:<ref>[http://www.telephonehouse.org.uk/telephonehouse/telerealprofile.html BT selects Land Securities Trillium as preferred bidder for property portfolio] BT Group, 10 April 2001</ref>  after selling its shares in Telereal to WPG in 2007, Land Securities sold Trillium to WPG in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/constructionandproperty/4177423/Land-Securities-defends-750m-Trillium-sale.html|title=Land Securities defends \u00a3750m Trillium sale|publisher= Daily Telegraph|date=8 January 2009|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 31 March 2012, Francis Salway was succeeded as chief executive by [[Robert Noel (businessman)|Robert Noel]]. Noel was managing director of the company's London properties, having joined Land Securities in January 2010 from [[Great Portland Estates]] plc, where he had been property director since 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-24/land-securities-ceo-francis-salway-to-step-down-and-be-replaced-by-noel.html| title=Land Securities CEO Salway Is to Step Down for London Manager Robert Noel|publisher=Bloomberg |date=24 January 2012|accessdate=12 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 June 2017, Land Securities rebranded as Landsec. The registered company name remains Land Securities Group PLC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://landsec.com/experiences/future-trends/landsec/land-securities-meet-landsec|title=Land Securities, meet Landsec {{!}} Landsec|website=landsec.com|language=en|access-date=2017-06-23}}</ref>\n\nRobert Noel stepped down as CEO on 31 March 2020. [https://landsec.com/about/management-team/martin-greenslade Martin Greenslade], the company's chief financial officer, is acting interim CEO until 14 April 2020. [https://landsec.com/media/press-releases/2020/ceo-appointment Mark Allan] joins Landsec as CEO on 14 April 2020. \n\n==Operations==\n[[File:Cardinal Place - geograph.org.uk - 965776.jpg|thumb|Cardinal Place, a development completed by Landsec in 2006|alt=100 Victoria Street, Cardinal Place photo]]\nLandsec owns and manages more than {{convert|24000000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} of commercial property, from London offices and high street shops to major shopping centres and out-of-town retail parks. At 31 March 2019 the company's property portfolio was valued at \u00a313.5 billion.<ref name=\"prelims\" /> The company owns the [[Piccadilly Circus#Illuminated signs|Piccadilly Lights]] in [[Piccadilly Circus]] in [[London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/constructionandproperty/8796119/Hyundai-in-lights-at-Londons-Piccadilly-Circus.html |title=Hyundai in lights at London\u2019s Piccadilly Circus|publisher= Daily Telegraph|date=29 September 2011|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref> It has also led Project Nova, the development of the area around [[London Victoria station]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.homesandproperty.co.uk/property-news/buying/new-homes/victorias-2billion-transformation-as-its-coach-station-becomes-a-cultural-quarter-with-homes-shops-29715.html|title=Victoria's \u00a32-billion transformation as its coach station becomes a cultural quarter with homes, shops and arts venues|publisher=Evening Standard|date=20 August 2013|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.landsec.com Official site]\n*[http://uk.finance.yahoo.com/q/pr?s=LAND.L Yahoo profile]\n\n{{Portal|Companies}}\n\n{{Land Securities}}\n{{Real estate in the United Kingdom}}\n{{FTSE 100 Index constituents}}\n[[Category:Real estate investment trusts of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the London Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Property companies based in London]]\n[[Category:British companies established in 1944]]\n[[Category:1944 establishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "Landsec", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Landsec"}
{"title_page": "Two Women", "text_new": "{{About|the 1960 Italian film||Two Women (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Two Women\n| image = TwoWomenPoster.jpg\n| caption = UK [[film poster]]<!-- poster names MGM as distributor- below, MGM listed as distributor for Rest of World outside US and Italy, hence US seems unlikely- reverted to previous -->\n| director = [[Vittorio De Sica]]\n| producer = [[Carlo Ponti]]\n| writer = [[Cesare Zavattini]]<br />'''Uncredited:'''<br>Vittorio De Sica\n| based on = ''[[Two Women (novel)|Two Women]]''<br>by [[Alberto Moravia]]\n| starring = [[Sophia Loren]]<br />[[Jean-Paul Belmondo]]<br>[[Raf Vallone]]<br />[[Eleonora Brown]]\n | music = [[Armando Trovajoli]]\n | cinematography = [[G\u00e1bor Pog\u00e1ny]]\n| editing = Adriana Novelli\n| studio = Compagnia Cinematografica Champion<br>Cocinor<br>Les Films Marceau<br>Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9n\u00e9rale de Cin\u00e9matographie (S.G.C.) \n| distributor = [[Titanus Distribuzione]] {{small|(Italy)}}<br>[[Embassy Pictures]] {{small|(US)}}<br>[[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] {{small|(International)}}\n| released = {{Film date|df=y|1960|12|22}}\n| runtime = 100 minutes\n| country = Italy<br>France\n| language = Italian<br />German\n| budget = \n|gross = $3.0 million (US and Canada rentals)<ref>{{cite news|title=Tracking the Players|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=January 18, 1993|page=36}}</ref><br>2,024,049 admissions (France)<ref>{{cite|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=fr&tl=en&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.boxofficestory.com%2Fbox-office-alain-delon-c22669761%2F39&sandbox=1|title= Box office information for Jean Paul Belmondo films|website=Box Office Story}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Two Women''''' ({{lang-it|'''La ciociara'''}} {{IPA-it|la t\u0283o\u02c8t\u0283a\u02d0ra|}}, rough literal translation \"The Woman from [[Ciociaria]]\") is a 1960 [[Cinema of Italy|Italian film]] directed by [[Vittorio De Sica]]. It tells the story of a woman trying to protect her young daughter from the horrors of war. The film stars [[Sophia Loren]], [[Jean-Paul Belmondo]], [[Raf Vallone]], [[Eleonora Brown]], [[Carlo Ninchi]], and [[Andrea Checchi]]. The film was adapted by De Sica and [[Cesare Zavattini]] from the [[Two women (novel)|novel of the same name]] written by [[Alberto Moravia]]. The story is fictional, but based on actual events of 1944 in Rome and rural [[Lazio]], during what Italians call the ''[[Marocchinate]]''.<ref>[http://www.cassino2000.com/cdsc/studi/archivio/n07/n07p09.html 1952: Il caso delle \u201cmarocchinate\u201d al Parlamento] Accessed 9 December 2017</ref>\n\nLoren's performance received critical acclaim, winning her the [[Academy Award for Best Actress]] among other accolades.\n\n==Plot==\nCesira (Loren) is a widowed shopkeeper, raising her devoutly religious twelve-year-old daughter, Rosetta (Brown), in Rome during [[World War II]]. Following the bombing of Rome, mother and daughter flee to Cesira's native [[Ciociaria]], a rural, mountainous province of central Italy. The night before they go, Cesira sleeps with Giovanni (Vallone), a coal dealer in her neighbourhood, who agrees to look after her store in her absence.\n\nAfter they arrive at Ciociaria, Cesira attracts the attention of Michele (Belmondo), a young local intellectual with [[communist]] sympathies. Rosetta sees Michele as a father figure and develops a strong bond with him. Michele is later taken prisoner by [[Wehrmacht|German soldiers]], who force him to act as a guide through the mountainous terrain.\n\nAfter the Allies capture Rome, in June 1944, Cesira and Rosetta decide to head back to that city. On the way, the two are gang-raped inside a church by a group of ''[[Moroccan Goumier]]s'' &ndash; soldiers attached to the invading [[Allied Armies in Italy]]. Rosetta is traumatized, becoming detached and distant from her mother and no longer an innocent child.\n\nWhen the two manage to find shelter at a neighbouring village, Rosetta disappears during the night, sending Cesira into a panic. She thinks Rosetta has gone to look for Michele, but later finds out that Michele was killed by the Germans. Rosetta returns, having been out with an older boy, who has given her silk stockings, despite her youth. Cesira is outraged and upset, slapping and spanking Rosetta for her behavior, but Rosetta remains unresponsive, emotionally distant. When Cesira informs Rosetta of Michele's death, Rosetta begins to cry like the little girl she had been prior to the rape. The film ends with Cesira comforting the child.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Sophia Loren]] as Cesira\n* [[Jean-Paul Belmondo]] as Michele Di Libero\n* [[Eleonora Brown]] as Rosetta\n* [[Carlo Ninchi]] as Filippo, Michele's father\n* [[Raf Vallone]] as Giovanni\n* [[Andrea Checchi]] as A fascist\n* [[Pupella Maggio]] as Peasant\n* Bruna Cealti as Refugee\n* Antonella Della Porta as A crazy mother\n* Mario Frera\n* [[Franco Balducci]] as German in the haystack\n* Luciana Cortellesi\n* [[Curt Lowens]]\n* Tony Calio\n* Remo Galavotti\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nThe film was based on a 1957 novel by [[Alberto Moravia]], ''La ciociara'' (''The Woman From Ciociaria''). It was inspired by Moravia's experiences during World War II.\n\n[[Carlo Ponti]] bought the film rights along with Marcello Girosi for a reported US$100,000. Sophia Loren was always meant to star and there was some talk that the film might be financed by Paramount, with whom Loren had made a number of movies.<ref>{{cite news|title=JAPANESE MOVIE WILL BE ADAPTED: Alciona, U. S. Concern, to Make 'Magnificent 7' -- Moravia Novel Eyed|first=Thomas|last=Pryor|newspaper=New York Times|date=13 May 1958|page= 26}}</ref> [[Anna Magnani]] was going to play the lead and Loren was going to be her daughter. [[George Cukor]] was going to direct as part of a two-picture deal with Ponti, the other one being ''[[Heller in Pink Tights]]'' (1960).<ref>{{cite news|title=FILM EVENTS: Cukor to Direct Loren|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=4 June 1958|page= C8}}</ref> The film was going to be shot as part of a six-picture deal between Ponti and Paramount.<ref>{{cite news|title=PRODUCERS PLAN 6 PICTURES BY '61: Ponti and Girosi Will Work With Paramount -- Studio Plans Consolidation|first=Thomas|last=Pryor|newspaper=New York Times|date=6 February 1959|page= 21}}</ref> \n\nCukor and Paramount dropped out. Vittorio De Sica became attached as director. Magnani pulled out, supposedly because she did not want to play Loren's mother, leading to Loren taking Magnani's role, even though the former was only 26 at the time.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4QhnLOpcLfcC&pg=PA77&lpg=PA77&dq=two+women+film+sophia+loren&source=bl&ots=MFIgxGKCYt&sig=icLi59fPVX-yzZzm_cITzdzotlc&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiA9ZDOvbTPAhWDFZQKHXcMBY84ChDoAQhUMA0#v=onepage&q=two%20women%20film%20sophia%20loren&f=false|page=77|title=Sophia Loren: Moulding the Star|first=Pauline|last= Small|publisher=Intellect Books|year=2009}}</ref> However, De Sica says it was his decision for Loren to play Magnani's role and cast a younger performer as the daughter \"for great poignancy. If, in doing this, we moved away from original line of Moravia, we had better opportunity to stress, to underline, the monstrous impact of war on people. The historical truth is that the great majority of those raped were young girls.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=De Sica Would Dig for 'Deepest Layer': Ace 'Two Women' Director Says Realism Still Dominant|last=Scheuer|first= Philip K.|newspaper= Los Angeles Times|date=27 Nov 1961|page= C15}}</ref> In a 2017 interview, Brown stated that Loren protected her from some of the underlying implications of the rape scene in the film, and also stated that director De Sica brought her to tears for the climatic final scene of hearing that Belmondo's character has died, by saying that a telegram had arrived saying that Brown's parents had died in an accident.<ref name=BrownReturns>{{cite news |url=http://www.ilgiornale.it/news/spettacoli/piccola-ciociara-torna-cinema-1459511.html |title=La piccola \"Ciociara\" torna al cinema |first=Paolo |last=Scotti |work=[[Il Giornale]] |date=2017-11-04 |accessdate=2018-02-25}}</ref>\n\nMagnani said she was going to do it, \"Moravia wanted me, but Ponti got it, and Moravia did not fight. After that, they went through all the roles I'd turned down for Sophia Loren to play.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=In the Beginning There Was Magnani. Then Came Loren. 'Ecco!'|first=Mark|last=Shivasrome|newspaper=New York Times |date=29 Sep 1968|page= D17}}</ref> \"The book was one of the most beautiful I've ever read\", said Loren. \"I thought it was worth taking the risk at 25 to play an older woman because the story was so beautiful.\"<ref name=\"desire\">{{cite news|title=Positively Sophia: Sophia Loren talks about movies, her husband and children, being 40, and the power of positive thinking|first=Karin|last= von Faber|newspaper= Chicago Tribune|date=27 Oct 1974|page= h56}}</ref> \nLoren later said her performance was inspired by her memories of her mother during the war.<ref>{{cite news|title=The actress wins an Oscar--and a name|newspaper=Chicago Tribune |date=21 March 1979|page= b1}}</ref> She also said she was greatly helped by her experience acting in ''[[Desire Under the Elms (film)|Desire Under the Elms]]'' (1958).<ref name=\"desire\"/>\n\nPonti raised money from France and Italy. French investment was conditional upon a French star being used, which lead to the casting of [[Jean Paul Belmondo]], who had leapt to international fame in ''Breathless'' (1960). Belmondo's voice was dubbed into Italian.\n\n==Release==\nJoseph E. Levine agreed to buy US release rights after watching only nine minutes of the film.<ref>{{cite news|title=MOVIE PRODUCER SELLS THE PUBLIC: Joseph E. Levine Believes in Extravagant Openings|first=Murray|last=Schumach|newspaper=New York Times|date=9 Nov 1961|page= 39}}</ref> \"I bet Sophia she'd win the Oscar and I nursed that film like a baby\", Levine later said.<ref name=\"joe\">{{cite news|title=Self-Made Mogul Hangs On: Joseph E. Levine, 82, Is Still Wheeling and Dealing|last=Rosenthal|first= Donna|newspaper= Los Angeles Times|date=5 July 1987|page= K23}}</ref> He showed the film in every city that a member of the Academy jury lived and promoted it assiduously. \"That showed foreign films could get big audiences if promoted with flair\", said Levine.<ref name=\"joe\"/>\n\nThe movie was among the 30 most popular films at the French box office that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=fr&tl=en&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.boxofficestory.com%2Fbox-office-alain-delon-c22669761%2F39&sandbox=1|title=1961 Box Office|website=Box Office Story}}</ref>\n\n== Recognitions ==\n* '''[[34th Academy Awards|1962 Academy Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] to [[Sophia Loren]]\n* '''[[15th British Academy Film Awards|1962 British Academy of Film and Television Arts Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|Best Film Actress in a Leading Role]] to [[Sophia Loren]]\n* '''[[19th Golden Globe Awards|1962 Golden Globe Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[Golden Globe Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Foreign Language]] ([[Italy]])\n* '''[[1961 Cannes Film Festival]]'''\n** (Nominated) [[Golden Palm|Golden Palm Award for Best Film]] to [[Vittorio De Sica]] \n** ('''Won''') [[Cannes Film Festival Award for Best Actress|Best Actress Award (Prix d'interpr\u00e9tation f\u00e9minine)]] to [[Sophia Loren]]\n* '''[[1960 in film|1961 David di Donatello Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[David di Donatello for Best Actress|Best Actress in a Leading Role]] to [[Sophia Loren]]\n* '''[[Nastri d'argento|1961 Silver Ribbons Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[Nastri d'argento|Best Leading Actress]] to [[Sophia Loren]]\n* '''[[1961 New York Film Critics Circle Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Actress|Best Lead Actress]] to [[Sophia Loren]]\n* '''[[National Board of Review Awards|1961 National Board of Review Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[National Board of Review Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Top 10 Foreign Language Films of the Year]] to [[Vittorio De Sica]]\n\n====Notes====\nThe film was heavily promoted by its North American distributor, [[Joseph E. Levine]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Joseph E. Levine|date=2019-10-03|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Joseph_E._Levine&oldid=919420756|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref> This was the first time an acting Oscar had been given for a non-[[English language|English]]-speaking performance ([[Sophia Loren]], [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress Oscar]] winner), although she made the English dubbing for her role herself. Loren was too nervous to attend the ceremony and elected to stay in Rome instead. [[Greer Garson]] accepted the award on Loren's behalf.\n\n==Remakes==\n''La Ciociara'' was remade for television in 1988. It was adapted by [[Diana Gould (writer)|Diana Gould]], [[Lidia Ravera]], [[Dino Risi]], and [[Bernardino Zapponi]]. It was directed by Risi, and starred Loren, [[Robert Loggia]], Leonardo Ferrantini, Dario Ghirardi, and [[Sydney Penny]]. An opera, La Ciociara, in a re-write by scenario writer Luca Rossi, with music composed by [[Marco Tutino]], received its premiere at San Francisco Opera,<ref>[https://www.opera-online.com/en/items/productions/two-women-la-ciociara-san-francisco-opera-2015-2015 Two Women (La Ciociara) - premiered at San Francisco Opera - Composer: Marco Tutino] Accessed 9 December 2017</ref> and a European premiere at [[Teatro Lirico di Cagliari|Teatro Lirico, Cagliari]].<ref>[http://www.ansa.it/sardegna/notizie/2017/11/21/cagliari-prima-europea-de-la-ciociara_e18a40da-f97e-4e35-aee9-e644c4aff8d5.html \"Cagliari, prima europea de La Ciociara Compositore Tutino, ''una storia di cui si parla poco''\" at ansa.it/sardegna] Accessed 13 December 2017</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|La Ciociara (film)}}\n*{{IMDb title|0054749|Two Women}}\n*{{Rotten Tomatoes|two_women}}\n*[http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/99299%7C0/Two-Women.html ''Two Women''] at [[TCMDB]]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=EE05E7DF173FE177BC4153DFB366838A679EDE Review of film] at [[New York Times]]\n*[http://www.lefilmguide.com/review/la-ciociara-1960.html Film page] at Le Film Guide\n{{Vittorio De Sica}}\n\n[[Category:Italian films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Rome]]\n[[Category:Films set in Lazio]]\n[[Category:1960 films]]\n[[Category:1960s drama films]]\n[[Category:Italian black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films about rape]]\n[[Category:Films based on Italian novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by Alberto Moravia]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Vittorio De Sica]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Actress Academy Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Carlo Ponti]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Armando Trovajoli]]\n[[Category:Italian Campaign of World War II films]]\n[[Category:Italian-language films]]\n[[Category:Italian neorealist films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Cesare Zavattini]]\n[[Category:Wartime sexual violence in World War II]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the 1960 Italian film||Two Women (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Two Women\n| image = TwoWomenPoster.jpg\n| caption = UK [[film poster]]<!-- poster names MGM as distributor- below, MGM listed as distributor for Rest of World outside US and Italy, hence US seems unlikely- reverted to previous -->\n| director = [[Vittorio De Sica]]\n| producer = [[Carlo Ponti]]\n| writer = [[Cesare Zavattini]]<br />'''Uncredited:'''<br>Vittorio De Sica\n| based on = ''[[Two Women (novel)|Two Women]]''<br>by [[Alberto Moravia]]\n| starring = [[Sophia Loren]]<br />[[Jean-Paul Belmondo]]<br>[[Raf Vallone]]<br />[[Eleonora Brown]]\n | music = [[Armando Trovajoli]]\n | cinematography = [[G\u00e1bor Pog\u00e1ny]]\n| editing = Adriana Novelli\n| studio = Compagnia Cinematografica Champion<br>Cocinor<br>Les Films Marceau<br>Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9n\u00e9rale de Cin\u00e9matographie (S.G.C.) \n| distributor = [[Titanus Distribuzione]] {{small|(Italy)}}<br>[[Embassy Pictures]] {{small|(US)}}<br>[[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] {{small|(International)}}\n| released = {{Film date|df=y|1960|12|22}}\n| runtime = 100 minutes\n| country = Italy<br>France\n| language = Italian<br />German\n| budget = \n|gross = $3.0 million (US and Canada rentals)<ref>{{cite news|title=Tracking the Players|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=January 18, 1993|page=36}}</ref><br>2,024,049 admissions (France)<ref>{{cite|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=fr&tl=en&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.boxofficestory.com%2Fbox-office-alain-delon-c22669761%2F39&sandbox=1|title= Box office information for Jean Paul Belmondo films|website=Box Office Story}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Two Women''''' ({{lang-it|'''La ciociara'''}} {{IPA-it|la t\u0283o\u02c8t\u0283a\u02d0ra|}}, rough literal translation \"The Woman from [[Ciociaria]]\") is a 1960 [[Cinema of Italy|Italian film]] directed by [[Vittorio De Sica]]. It tells the story of a woman trying to protect her young daughter from the horrors of war. The film stars [[Sophia Loren]], [[Jean-Paul Belmondo]], [[Raf Vallone]], [[Eleonora Brown]], [[Carlo Ninchi]], and [[Andrea Checchi]]. The film was adapted by De Sica and [[Cesare Zavattini]] from the [[Two women (novel)|novel of the same name]] written by [[Alberto Moravia]]. The story is fictional, but based on actual events of 1944 in Rome and rural [[Lazio]], during what Italians call the ''[[Marocchinate]]''.<ref>[http://www.cassino2000.com/cdsc/studi/archivio/n07/n07p09.html 1952: Il caso delle \u201cmarocchinate\u201d al Parlamento] Accessed 9 December 2017</ref>\n\nLoren's performance received critical acclaim, winning her the [[Academy Award for Best Actress]] among other accolades.\n\n==Plot==\nCesira (Loren) is a widowed shopkeeper, raising her devoutly religious twelve-year-old daughter, Rosetta (Brown), in Rome during [[World War II]]. Following the bombing of Romw, mother and daughter flee to Cesira's native [[Ciociaria]], a rural, mountainous province of central Italy. The night before they go, Cesira sleeps with Giovanni (Vallone), a coal dealer in her neighbourhood, who agrees to look after her store in her absence.\n\nAfter they arrive at Ciociaria, Cesira attracts the attention of Michele (Belmondo), a young local intellectual with [[communist]] sympathies. Rosetta sees Michele as a father figure and develops a strong bond with him. Michele is later taken prisoner by [[Wehrmacht|German soldiers]], who force him to act as a guide through the mountainous terrain.\n\nAfter the Allies capture Rome, in June 1944, Cesira and Rosetta decide to head back to that city. On the way, the two are gang-raped inside a church by a group of ''[[Moroccan Goumier]]s'' &ndash; soldiers attached to the invading [[Allied Armies in Italy]]. Rosetta is traumatized, becoming detached and distant from her mother and no longer an innocent child.\n\nWhen the two manage to find shelter at a neighbouring village, Rosetta disappears during the night, sending Cesira into a panic. She thinks Rosetta has gone to look for Michele, but later finds out that Michele was killed by the Germans. Rosetta returns, having been out with an older boy, who has given her silk stockings, despite her youth. Cesira is outraged and upset, slapping and spanking Rosetta for her behavior, but Rosetta remains unresponsive, emotionally distant. When Cesira informs Rosetta of Michele's death, Rosetta begins to cry like the little girl she had been prior to the rape. The film ends with Cesira comforting the child.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Sophia Loren]] as Cesira\n* [[Jean-Paul Belmondo]] as Michele Di Libero\n* [[Eleonora Brown]] as Rosetta\n* [[Carlo Ninchi]] as Filippo, Michele's father\n* [[Raf Vallone]] as Giovanni\n* [[Andrea Checchi]] as A fascist\n* [[Pupella Maggio]] as Peasant\n* Bruna Cealti as Refugee\n* Antonella Della Porta as A crazy mother\n* Mario Frera\n* [[Franco Balducci]] as German in the haystack\n* Luciana Cortellesi\n* [[Curt Lowens]]\n* Tony Calio\n* Remo Galavotti\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nThe film was based on a 1957 novel by [[Alberto Moravia]], ''La ciociara'' (''The Woman From Ciociaria''). It was inspired by Moravia's experiences during World War II.\n\n[[Carlo Ponti]] bought the film rights along with Marcello Girosi for a reported US$100,000. Sophia Loren was always meant to star and there was some talk that the film might be financed by Paramount, with whom Loren had made a number of movies.<ref>{{cite news|title=JAPANESE MOVIE WILL BE ADAPTED: Alciona, U. S. Concern, to Make 'Magnificent 7' -- Moravia Novel Eyed|first=Thomas|last=Pryor|newspaper=New York Times|date=13 May 1958|page= 26}}</ref> [[Anna Magnani]] was going to play the lead and Loren was going to be her daughter. [[George Cukor]] was going to direct as part of a two-picture deal with Ponti, the other one being ''[[Heller in Pink Tights]]'' (1960).<ref>{{cite news|title=FILM EVENTS: Cukor to Direct Loren|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=4 June 1958|page= C8}}</ref> The film was going to be shot as part of a six-picture deal between Ponti and Paramount.<ref>{{cite news|title=PRODUCERS PLAN 6 PICTURES BY '61: Ponti and Girosi Will Work With Paramount -- Studio Plans Consolidation|first=Thomas|last=Pryor|newspaper=New York Times|date=6 February 1959|page= 21}}</ref> \n\nCukor and Paramount dropped out. Vittorio De Sica became attached as director. Magnani pulled out, supposedly because she did not want to play Loren's mother, leading to Loren taking Magnani's role, even though the former was only 26 at the time.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4QhnLOpcLfcC&pg=PA77&lpg=PA77&dq=two+women+film+sophia+loren&source=bl&ots=MFIgxGKCYt&sig=icLi59fPVX-yzZzm_cITzdzotlc&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiA9ZDOvbTPAhWDFZQKHXcMBY84ChDoAQhUMA0#v=onepage&q=two%20women%20film%20sophia%20loren&f=false|page=77|title=Sophia Loren: Moulding the Star|first=Pauline|last= Small|publisher=Intellect Books|year=2009}}</ref> However, De Sica says it was his decision for Loren to play Magnani's role and cast a younger performer as the daughter \"for great poignancy. If, in doing this, we moved away from original line of Moravia, we had better opportunity to stress, to underline, the monstrous impact of war on people. The historical truth is that the great majority of those raped were young girls.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=De Sica Would Dig for 'Deepest Layer': Ace 'Two Women' Director Says Realism Still Dominant|last=Scheuer|first= Philip K.|newspaper= Los Angeles Times|date=27 Nov 1961|page= C15}}</ref> In a 2017 interview, Brown stated that Loren protected her from some of the underlying implications of the rape scene in the film, and also stated that director De Sica brought her to tears for the climatic final scene of hearing that Belmondo's character has died, by saying that a telegram had arrived saying that Brown's parents had died in an accident.<ref name=BrownReturns>{{cite news |url=http://www.ilgiornale.it/news/spettacoli/piccola-ciociara-torna-cinema-1459511.html |title=La piccola \"Ciociara\" torna al cinema |first=Paolo |last=Scotti |work=[[Il Giornale]] |date=2017-11-04 |accessdate=2018-02-25}}</ref>\n\nMagnani said she was going to do it, \"Moravia wanted me, but Ponti got it, and Moravia did not fight. After that, they went through all the roles I'd turned down for Sophia Loren to play.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=In the Beginning There Was Magnani. Then Came Loren. 'Ecco!'|first=Mark|last=Shivasrome|newspaper=New York Times |date=29 Sep 1968|page= D17}}</ref> \"The book was one of the most beautiful I've ever read\", said Loren. \"I thought it was worth taking the risk at 25 to play an older woman because the story was so beautiful.\"<ref name=\"desire\">{{cite news|title=Positively Sophia: Sophia Loren talks about movies, her husband and children, being 40, and the power of positive thinking|first=Karin|last= von Faber|newspaper= Chicago Tribune|date=27 Oct 1974|page= h56}}</ref> \nLoren later said her performance was inspired by her memories of her mother during the war.<ref>{{cite news|title=The actress wins an Oscar--and a name|newspaper=Chicago Tribune |date=21 March 1979|page= b1}}</ref> She also said she was greatly helped by her experience acting in ''[[Desire Under the Elms (film)|Desire Under the Elms]]'' (1958).<ref name=\"desire\"/>\n\nPonti raised money from France and Italy. French investment was conditional upon a French star being used, which lead to the casting of [[Jean Paul Belmondo]], who had leapt to international fame in ''Breathless'' (1960). Belmondo's voice was dubbed into Italian.\n\n==Release==\nJoseph E. Levine agreed to buy US release rights after watching only nine minutes of the film.<ref>{{cite news|title=MOVIE PRODUCER SELLS THE PUBLIC: Joseph E. Levine Believes in Extravagant Openings|first=Murray|last=Schumach|newspaper=New York Times|date=9 Nov 1961|page= 39}}</ref> \"I bet Sophia she'd win the Oscar and I nursed that film like a baby\", Levine later said.<ref name=\"joe\">{{cite news|title=Self-Made Mogul Hangs On: Joseph E. Levine, 82, Is Still Wheeling and Dealing|last=Rosenthal|first= Donna|newspaper= Los Angeles Times|date=5 July 1987|page= K23}}</ref> He showed the film in every city that a member of the Academy jury lived and promoted it assiduously. \"That showed foreign films could get big audiences if promoted with flair\", said Levine.<ref name=\"joe\"/>\n\nThe movie was among the 30 most popular films at the French box office that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=fr&tl=en&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.boxofficestory.com%2Fbox-office-alain-delon-c22669761%2F39&sandbox=1|title=1961 Box Office|website=Box Office Story}}</ref>\n\n== Recognitions ==\n* '''[[34th Academy Awards|1962 Academy Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] to [[Sophia Loren]]\n* '''[[15th British Academy Film Awards|1962 British Academy of Film and Television Arts Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|Best Film Actress in a Leading Role]] to [[Sophia Loren]]\n* '''[[19th Golden Globe Awards|1962 Golden Globe Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[Golden Globe Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Foreign Language]] ([[Italy]])\n* '''[[1961 Cannes Film Festival]]'''\n** (Nominated) [[Golden Palm|Golden Palm Award for Best Film]] to [[Vittorio De Sica]] \n** ('''Won''') [[Cannes Film Festival Award for Best Actress|Best Actress Award (Prix d'interpr\u00e9tation f\u00e9minine)]] to [[Sophia Loren]]\n* '''[[1960 in film|1961 David di Donatello Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[David di Donatello for Best Actress|Best Actress in a Leading Role]] to [[Sophia Loren]]\n* '''[[Nastri d'argento|1961 Silver Ribbons Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[Nastri d'argento|Best Leading Actress]] to [[Sophia Loren]]\n* '''[[1961 New York Film Critics Circle Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Actress|Best Lead Actress]] to [[Sophia Loren]]\n* '''[[National Board of Review Awards|1961 National Board of Review Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[National Board of Review Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Top 10 Foreign Language Films of the Year]] to [[Vittorio De Sica]]\n\n====Notes====\nThe film was heavily promoted by its North American distributor, [[Joseph E. Levine]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Joseph E. Levine|date=2019-10-03|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Joseph_E._Levine&oldid=919420756|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref> This was the first time an acting Oscar had been given for a non-[[English language|English]]-speaking performance ([[Sophia Loren]], [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress Oscar]] winner), although she made the English dubbing for her role herself. Loren was too nervous to attend the ceremony and elected to stay in Rome instead. [[Greer Garson]] accepted the award on Loren's behalf.\n\n==Remakes==\n''La Ciociara'' was remade for television in 1988. It was adapted by [[Diana Gould (writer)|Diana Gould]], [[Lidia Ravera]], [[Dino Risi]], and [[Bernardino Zapponi]]. It was directed by Risi, and starred Loren, [[Robert Loggia]], Leonardo Ferrantini, Dario Ghirardi, and [[Sydney Penny]]. An opera, La Ciociara, in a re-write by scenario writer Luca Rossi, with music composed by [[Marco Tutino]], received its premiere at San Francisco Opera,<ref>[https://www.opera-online.com/en/items/productions/two-women-la-ciociara-san-francisco-opera-2015-2015 Two Women (La Ciociara) - premiered at San Francisco Opera - Composer: Marco Tutino] Accessed 9 December 2017</ref> and a European premiere at [[Teatro Lirico di Cagliari|Teatro Lirico, Cagliari]].<ref>[http://www.ansa.it/sardegna/notizie/2017/11/21/cagliari-prima-europea-de-la-ciociara_e18a40da-f97e-4e35-aee9-e644c4aff8d5.html \"Cagliari, prima europea de La Ciociara Compositore Tutino, ''una storia di cui si parla poco''\" at ansa.it/sardegna] Accessed 13 December 2017</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|La Ciociara (film)}}\n*{{IMDb title|0054749|Two Women}}\n*{{Rotten Tomatoes|two_women}}\n*[http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/99299%7C0/Two-Women.html ''Two Women''] at [[TCMDB]]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=EE05E7DF173FE177BC4153DFB366838A679EDE Review of film] at [[New York Times]]\n*[http://www.lefilmguide.com/review/la-ciociara-1960.html Film page] at Le Film Guide\n{{Vittorio De Sica}}\n\n[[Category:Italian films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Rome]]\n[[Category:Films set in Lazio]]\n[[Category:1960 films]]\n[[Category:1960s drama films]]\n[[Category:Italian black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films about rape]]\n[[Category:Films based on Italian novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by Alberto Moravia]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Vittorio De Sica]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Actress Academy Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Carlo Ponti]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Armando Trovajoli]]\n[[Category:Italian Campaign of World War II films]]\n[[Category:Italian-language films]]\n[[Category:Italian neorealist films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Cesare Zavattini]]\n[[Category:Wartime sexual violence in World War II]]\n", "name_user": "Vic joseph", "label": "safe", "comment": "Romw -> Rome", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Two_Women"}
{"title_page": "Revolutionary War Door", "text_new": "{{Infobox artwork\n| italic title       = no\n| image_file         = Flickr - USCapitol - House Bronze Doors.jpg\n| image_upright      = 1\n| painting_alignment = Front\n| image_size         = \n| title              = Revolutionary War Door\n| alt                =\n| other_language_1   = \n| other_title_1      = \n| other_language_2   =\n| other_title_2      =\n| artist             = [[Thomas Crawford (sculptor)|Thomas Crawford]]\n| year               = {{Start date|1905}}\n| type               = Bronze\n| height_metric      =\n| width_metric       =\n| length_metric      =\n| height_imperial    = 14\n| height_inch        = 5\n| width_imperial     = \n| length_imperial    = \n| metric_unit        = m\n| imperial_unit      = ft\n| city               = [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]]\n| museum             = \n| coordinates        = \n| owner              = [[Architect of the Capitol]]\n}}\n''\nThe '''Revolutionary War Door''' is an artwork by American sculptor [[Thomas Crawford (sculptor)|Thomas Crawford]], located on the [[United States Capitol]] House of Representatives wing east front in [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]]. This sculptured door was surveyed in 1993 as part of the [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian's]] [[Save Outdoor Sculpture!]] program.<ref name=\"SOS\">{{cite web | author=Smithsonian | year=1993 | title=Revolutionary War Door, (sculpture). | work=Save Outdoor Sculpture | publisher=Smithsonian | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!4884~!0#focus | accessdate= 16 Feb 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n\nThese two elaborate doors consist of six panel medallions that depict activities and events during the [[American Revolution]].<ref name=\"SOS\"/>\n\nThe left panel, top to bottom, depicts:\n\n*The [[Battle of Wyoming]]\n*The [[Battles of Lexington and Concord|Battle of Lexington]]\n*The presentation of the flag and medal to Major General [[Nathanael Greene]]\n*The death of Major General [[Richard Montgomery]]\n\nThe right panel, top to bottom, depicts:\n\n*The public reading of the [[United States Declaration of Independence]] in Philadelphia\n*The [[Peace of Paris (1783)|Peace of Paris]]\n*[[George Washington|George Washington's]] farewell to his officers in New York at [[Fraunces Tavern]]\n*[[Benjamin Franklin]] working in his studio<ref name=\"SOS\"/>\n\n==History==\nCrawford designed the doors in [[Rome, Italy|Rome]] between 1855 and 1857. Crawford died in 1857, leaving [[William H. Rinehart]] to create the models from Crawford's original sketches during the years of 1863\u20131867. The models were stored in the crypt of the Capitol until they were cast in 1904 and installed in 1905.<ref name=\"SOS\"/>\n\nIn 1993 the door was analyzed by art conservators from the Save Outdoor Sculpture! survey program and was described as well-maintained.<ref name=\"SOS\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of public art in Washington, D.C., Ward 6]]\n\n==Further reading==\n\n*Allen, William C. ''History of the United States Capitol: A Chronicle of Design, Construction, and Politics''. Architect of the Capitol, 2001. {{ISBN|0-16-050830-4}}\n*Wood, James M. ''Washington Sculpture''. Johns Hopkins Press, 2008. {{ISBN|0-8018-8810-7}}\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Visual arts}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{United States Capitol Complex}}\n{{Public art in Washington, D.C.}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1905 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:1905 sculptures]]\n[[Category:American Revolutionary War]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:George Washington in art]]\n[[Category:Individual doors]]\n[[Category:United States Capitol]]\n[[Category:United States Declaration of Independence]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of men in Washington, D.C.]]\n\n{{public-art-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artwork\n| image_file = Flickr - USCapitol - House Bronze Doors.jpg\n| painting_alignment = Front\n| image_size         = 300px\n| title              = Revolutionary War Door\n| alt                =\n| other_language_1   = \n| other_title_1      = \n| other_language_2   =\n| other_title_2      =\n| artist             = Thomas Crawford (sculptor)\n| year               = {{Start date|1905}}\n| type               = Bronze\n| height_metric      =\n| width_metric       =\n| length_metric      =\n| height_imperial    = 14\n| height_inch        = 5\n| width_imperial     = \n| length_imperial    = \n| metric_unit        = m\n| imperial_unit      = ft\n| city               = [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]]\n| museum             = \n| coordinates        = \n| owner              = [[Architect of the Capitol]]\n}}\n''\n'''''Revolutionary War Door''''' is an artwork by American sculptor [[Thomas Crawford (sculptor)|Thomas Crawford]], located on the [[United States Capitol]] House of Representatives wing east front in [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]]. This sculptured door was surveyed in 1993 as part of the [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian's]] [[Save Outdoor Sculpture!]] program.<ref name=\"SOS\">{{cite web | author=Smithsonian | year=1993 | title=Revolutionary War Door, (sculpture). | work=Save Outdoor Sculpture | publisher=Smithsonian | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!4884~!0#focus | accessdate= 16 Feb 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n\nThese two elaborate doors consist of six panel medallions that depict activities and events during the [[American Revolution]].<ref name=\"SOS\"/>\n\nThe left panel, top to bottom, depicts:\n\n*The [[Battle of Wyoming]]\n*The [[Battles of Lexington and Concord|Battle of Lexington]]\n*The presentation of the flag and medal to Major General [[Nathanael Greene]]\n*The death of Major General [[Richard Montgomery]]\n\nThe right panel, top to bottom, depicts:\n\n*The public reading of the [[United States Declaration of Independence]] in Philadelphia\n*The [[Peace of Paris (1783)|Peace of Paris]]\n*[[George Washington|George Washington's]] farewell to his officers in New York at [[Fraunces Tavern]]\n*[[Benjamin Franklin]] working in his studio<ref name=\"SOS\"/>\n\n==History==\nCrawford designed the doors in [[Rome, Italy|Rome]] between 1855&ndash;57. Crawford died in 1857, leaving [[William H. Rinehart]] to create the models from Crawford's original sketches during the years of 1863&ndash;67. The models were stored in the crypt of the Capitol until they were cast in 1904 and installed in 1905.<ref name=\"SOS\"/>\n\nIn 1993 the door was analyzed by art conservators from the Save Outdoor Sculpture! survey program and was described as well-maintained.<ref name=\"SOS\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of public art in Washington, D.C., Ward 6]]\n\n==Further reading==\n\n*Allen, William C. ''History of the United States Capitol: A Chronicle of Design, Construction, and Politics''. Architect of the Capitol, 2001. {{ISBN|0-16-050830-4}}\n*Wood, James M. ''Washington Sculpture''. Johns Hopkins Press, 2008. {{ISBN|0-8018-8810-7}}\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Visual arts}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{United States Capitol Complex}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1905 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:1905 sculptures]]\n[[Category:American Revolutionary War]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:George Washington in art]]\n[[Category:Individual doors]]\n[[Category:United States Capitol]]\n[[Category:United States Declaration of Independence]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of men in Washington, D.C.]]\n\n{{public-art-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ham II", "label": "safe", "comment": "+Template:Public art in Washington, D.C.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Revolutionary_War_Door"}
{"title_page": "Bushey Heath tube station", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox London station\n| name=Bushey Heath\n| image_name=\n| gridref=TQ164950\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.64176|-0.31924|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| map_type=Hertfordshire\n| owner=Never Opened\n| original=[[London Underground]]\n| locale=[[Bushey Heath]]\n| platforms=4 (planned but never built)\n}}\n\n'''Bushey Heath''' was a proposed, but unbuilt, [[London Underground]] station in [[Bushey Heath]], [[Hertfordshire]]. The planned location of the station was at the junction of the [[A41 road|A41]] and [[A411 road]]s.\n\n==History==\n===Planning===\n[[File:Bushey Heath Extension superimposed on 1934 OS Map.jpg|thumb|300px|left|Planned route of the Bushey Heath extension superimposed on a 1934 map showing the rural nature of the area]]\nThe station was the last of three planned by [[London Passenger Transport Board]] (LPTB) in 1935 for an extension of the [[Northern line]] from [[Edgware]].{{sfn|Horne|2009|p=42}} It would have served as the new terminus of the line. There was debate about the name for the station, with ''West Elstree'', ''Caldecote Hill'', ''South Aldenham'', ''Aldenham'', ''Bushey Heath and Aldenham'' and ''Bushey and Aldenham'' being proposed.{{sfn|Beard|2002|pp=60\u201364}}{{#tag:ref|A protracted, series of discussions within the LPTB and with other interested parties took place during 1937 and 1938. The name used during much of planning stages was \"Aldenham\", linked to the nearby village (although [[Aldenham]] is further away from the proposed station site than both [[Elstree]] and [[Bushey Heath]]). The final choice of Bushey Heath was made in January 1938.{{sfn|Beard|2002|pp=60\u201364}}|group=\"n\"}} The previous station on the route would have been [[Elstree South tube station|Elstree South]] to the east.\n\nThe extension was part of the ''[[Northern line#The Northern Heights plan|Northern Heights]]'' project which was intended to electrify a number of steam-operated [[London and North Eastern Railway]] (LNER) branch lines and to incorporate them into the Northern line. Much of the land for the extension came from the purchase in 1922 by the LPTB's precursor the [[Underground Electric Railways Company of London]] of the unbuilt [[Watford and Edgware Railway]] (W&ER). The W&ER had planned an extension of the [[Edgware, Highgate and London Railway]] to [[Watford Junction]] via Bushey, but it had never raised the capital required and its powers to construct a line had expired in 1911.{{sfn|Beard|2002|p=14}} The specific route to Bushey Heath was approved by parliament in October 1937.{{sfn|Beard|2002|p=86}} The LPTB's principal purpose for the extension was to stimulate the development of new residential areas to increase passenger numbers.{{sfn|Beard|2002|pp=56\u201357}} A secondary purpose was to provide a location suitable for a large new depot that was required to accommodate and maintain the new fleet of [[London Underground 1938 Stock|1938 Stock trains]] to be used across the existing Northern line and the lines taken over from the LNER.{{sfn|Horne|2009|p=42}}{{sfn|Beard|2002|p=18}}{{#tag:ref|The Northern line's depot at [[Golders Green tube station|Golders Green]] and the [[Northern City Line|Northern City line's]] depot at [[Drayton Park railway station|Drayton Park]] were poorly arranged and unsuitable for the accommodation and maintenance of the new trains.{{sfn|Beard|2002|p=28}} The LPTB considered constructing a new depot alongside the LNER's line between [[Finchley Central tube station|Finchley Central]] and Edgware, but could not negotiate a deal with the local authority for a suitable site in time to enable the depot to be built before the new rolling stock was to be delivered.{{sfn|Beard|2002|pp=27\u201328}}|group=\"n\"}}{{#tag:ref|The arrangement of the depot at Aldenham located between Elstree South and Bushey Heath was intended to be similar to that  between [[Oakwood tube station|Oakwood]] and [[Cockfosters tube station|Cockfosters]] on the recently opened [[Piccadilly line]] extension.{{sfn|Beard|2002|p=53}}|group=\"n\"}} The depot was to be constructed to the south of the running tracks between Bushey Heath and Elstree South with access from each end.\n\nBushey Heath station was to be located on the east side of the roundabout junction of Watford By-pass ([[A41 road|A41]]) and Elstree Road (A411). The station would have had three tracks with two double-sided platforms.{{sfn|Beard|2002|p=34}} The arrangement placed the station entrance directly next to the roundabout preventing any later extension. The station was to be provided with a large bus station and car park.{{sfn|Beard|2002|p=67}} The LPTB planned to purchase the land on all four sides of the junction and proposed an extensive commercial development around the roundabout including a cinema, roadhouse and around 40 shops.{{sfn|Beard|2002|pp=32-33 & 67}}\n\n[[File:Bushey Heath Extension Mockup.svg|thumb|How Bushey Heath station may have looked on the [[London Underground Map]] if the [[Northern line]] extension from Edgware to Bushey Heath and Mill Hill East had been built]]\nConstruction work on the Northern Heights project began in the late 1930s but was suspended by the outbreak of the [[Second World War]]. Most of the work undertaken to that date had been carried out on the existing LNER branch tracks but some work between Edgware and Elstree had taken place, but work between Edgware and Bushey Heath had started in June 1939. The route of the line had been cleared and laid out and some earthworks and tunnelling carried out between Edgware and Elstree South.{{sfn|Beard|2002|p=90}}\n\nFollowing the outbreak of war in Europe, work on the extension was suspended in September 1939 and was formally terminated in December of the same year as wartime funding restrictions would prevent completion.{{sfn|Beard|2002|pp=92 & 129}} Construction of Bushey Heath station had not started when the Second World War began. During the war years, the LPTB-owned land was used for farming vegetables for staff canteens.{{sfn|Horne|2009|p=51}}\n\nWork on designs for the station continued during the war to make changes required to account for [[Department for Transport|Ministry of Transport]] plans to modify the roundabout to include an underpass. This moved the station from the east side of the roundabout to the north side with the lines running under Elstree Road. The revised arrangement would have allowed a continuation of the line beyond Bushey Heath.{{sfn|Horne|2009|p=97}}\n\n===Cancellation===\nThe sites of all three new stations were in semi-rural locations and, as had happened elsewhere, it was intended that the opening of the new section of Underground line would stimulate the construction of new residential estates that the stations would then serve. After the war, however, new legislation was introduced with the intention of limiting the continuing expansion of urban areas into the surrounding countryside. This legislation created the [[Metropolitan Green Belt]] around London and the area designated included the area covered by the new Northern line extension. Without the possibility of constructing the new housing estates, the new line had no purpose and the plans for the extension were cancelled in 1950.{{sfn|Beard|2002|p=126}} \n\nDuring the war, the depot buildings were used for the construction of [[Handley Page Halifax|Halifax]] bombers and the land owned by London Underground at Bushey was used for farming. After the abandonment of the extension plans, the depot buildings became [[Aldenham Works|Aldenham Bus Overhaul Works]].\n\nAs a result of the breakup of London Transport Buses and the devolving of maintenance functions to the depots of individual bus companies, the overhaul works ceased operation in 1986. The premises stood derelict until 1997 when it was demolished and replaced with the Centennial Business Park.\n\nFootage of the overhaul works in operation can be seen in the opening scenes of the 1963 film ''[[Summer Holiday (1963 film)|Summer Holiday]]'' starring [[Cliff Richard]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Edgware, Highgate and London Railway]] - LNER branch line taken over by London Underground as part of the Northern Heights project\n\n==Notes and references==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{ref begin}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beard |first=Tony |title=By Tube Beyond Edgware |publisher=Capital Transport |year=2002 |isbn=978-1-85414-246-7 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Horne |first=Mike |title=The Northern Line, An Illustrated History |year=2009 |origyear=1990 |edition=3rd |publisher=Capital Transport |isbn=978-1-85414-326-6 |ref=harv}}\n{{ref end}}\n\n==External links==\n* London Transport Museum Photographic Archive\n** {{ltmcollection|8q/i000078q.jpg|Land Girls working on London Transport farm at Bushey}}\n** {{ltmcollection|cs/i0000ecs.jpg|Bus overhaul works at Aldenham}}\n* [http://www.abandonedstations.org.uk/Northern_Heights_10.html Abandoned Tube Stations - Northern Heights: Edgware - Bushey Heath]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-note|text=Abandoned Northern Heights Extension |wide=yes }}\n{{s-rail|title=LUL}}\n{{s-line|system=LUL|line=Northern|next=Elstree South|type=Northern Heights|type2=South}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{closed london underground stations}}{{Northern line navbox}}\n{{Closed stations Hertfordshire}}\n\n[[Category:Hertsmere]]\n[[Category:Proposed London Underground stations]]\n[[Category:Unbuilt Northern Heights extension stations]]\n[[Category:Charles Holden railway stations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox London station\n| name=Bushey Heath\n| image_name=\n| gridref=TQ164950\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.64176|-0.31924|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| map_type=Hertfordshire\n| owner=Never Opened\n| original=[[London Underground]]\n| locale=[[Bushey Heath]]\n| platforms=4 (planned but never built)\n}}\n\n'''Bushey Heath''' was a proposed, but unbuilt, [[London Underground]] station in [[Bushey Heath]], [[Hertfordshire]]. The planned location of the station was at the junction of the [[A41 road|A41]] and [[A411 road]]s.\n\n==History==\n===Planning===\n[[File:Bushey Heath Extension superimposed on 1934 OS Map.jpg|thumb|300px|left|Planned route of the Bushey Heath extension superimposed on a 1934 map showing the rural nature of the area]]\nThe station was the last of three planned by [[London Passenger Transport Board]] (LPTB) in 1935 for an extension of the [[Northern line]] from [[Edgware]].{{sfn|Horne|2009|p=42}} It would have served as the new terminus of the line. There was debate about the name for the station, with ''West Elstree'', ''Caldecote Hill'', ''South Aldenham'', ''Aldenham'', ''Bushey Heath and Aldenham'' and ''Bushey and Aldenham'' being proposed.{{sfn|Beard|2002|pp=60\u201364}}{{#tag:ref|A protracted, series of discussions within the LPTB and with other interested parties took place during 1937 and 1938. The name used during much of planning stages was \"Aldenham\", linked to the nearby village (although [[Aldenham]] is further away from the proposed station site than both [[Elstree]] and [[Bushey Heath]]). The final choice of Bushey Heath was made in January 1938.{{sfn|Beard|2002|pp=60\u201364}}|group=\"n\"}} The previous station on the route would have been [[Elstree South tube station|Elstree South]] to the east.\n\nThe extension was part of the ''[[Northern line#The Northern Heights plan|Northern Heights]]'' project which was intended to electrify a number of steam-operated [[London and North Eastern Railway]] (LNER) branch lines and to incorporate them into the Northern line. Much of the land for the extension came from the purchase in 1922 by the LPTB's precursor the [[Underground Electric Railways Company of London]] of the unbuilt [[Watford and Edgware Railway]] (W&ER). The W&ER had planned an extension of the [[Edgware, Highgate and London Railway]] to [[Watford Junction]] via Bushey, but it had never raised the capital required and its powers to construct a line had expired in 1911.{{sfn|Beard|2002|p=14}} The specific route to Bushey Heath was approved by parliament in October 1937.{{sfn|Beard|2002|p=86}} The LPTB's principal purpose for the extension was to stimulate the development of new residential areas to increase passenger numbers.{{sfn|Beard|2002|pp=56\u201357}} A secondary purpose was to provide a location suitable for a large new depot that was required to accommodate and maintain the new fleet of [[London Underground 1938 Stock|1938 Stock trains]] to be used across the existing Northern line and the lines taken over from the LNER.{{sfn|Horne|2009|p=42}}{{sfn|Beard|2002|p=18}}{{#tag:ref|The Northern line's depot at [[Golders Green tube station|Golders Green]] and the [[Northern City Line|Northern City line's]] depot at [[Drayton Park railway station|Drayton Park]] were poorly arranged and unsuitable for the accommodation and maintenance of the new trains.{{sfn|Beard|2002|p=28}} The LPTB considered constructing a new depot alongside the LNER's line between [[Finchley Central tube station|Finchley Central]] and Edgware, but could not negotiate a deal with the local authority for a suitable site in time to enable the depot to be built before the new rolling stock was to be delivered.{{sfn|Beard|2002|pp=27\u201328}}|group=\"n\"}}{{#tag:ref|The arrangement of the depot at Aldenham located between Elstree South and Bushey Heath was intended to be similar to that  between [[Oakwood tube station|Oakwood]] and [[Cockfosters tube station|Cockfosters]] on the recently opened [[Piccadilly line]] extension.{{sfn|Beard|2002|p=53}}|group=\"n\"}} The depot was to be constructed to the south of the running tracks between Bushey Heath and Elstree South with access from each end.\n\nBushey Heath station was to be located on the east side of the roundabout junction of Watford By-pass ([[A41 road|A41]]) and Elstree Road (A411). The station would have had three tracks with two double-sided platforms.{{sfn|Beard|2002|p=34}} The arrangement placed the station entrance directly next to the roundabout preventing any later extension. The station was to be provided with a large bus station and car park.{{sfn|Beard|2002|p=67}} The LPTB planned to purchase the land on all four sides of the junction and proposed an extensive commercial development around the roundabout including a cinema, roadhouse and around 40 shops.{{sfn|Beard|2002|pp=32-33 & 67}}\n\n[[File:Bushey Heath Extension Mockup.svg|thumb|How Bushey Heath station may have looked on the [[London Underground Map]] if the [[Northern line]] extension from Edgware to Bushey Heath and Mill Hill East had been built]]\nConstruction work on the Northern Heights project began in the late 1930s but was suspended by the outbreak of the [[Second World War]]. Most of the work undertaken to that date had been carried out on the existing LNER branch tracks but some work between Edgware and Elstree had taken place, but work between Edgware and Bushey Heath had started in June 1939. The route of the line had been cleared and laid out and some earthworks and tunnelling carried out between Edgware and Elstree South.{{sfn|Beard|2002|p=90}}\n\nFollowing the outbreak of war in Europe, work on the extension was suspended in September 1939 and was formally terminated in December of the same year as wartime funding restrictions would prevent completion.{{sfn|Beard|2002|pp=92 & 129}} Construction of Bushey Heath station had not started when the Second World War began. During the war years, the LPTB-owned land was used for farming vegetables for staff canteens.{{sfn|Horne|2009|p=51}}\n\nWork on designs for the station continued during the war to make changes required to account for [[Department for Transport|Ministry of Transport]] plans to modify the roundabout to include an underpass. This moved the station from the east side of the roundabout to the north side  with the lines running under Elstree Road. The revised arrangement would have allowed a continuation of the line beyond Bushey Heath.{{sfn|Horne|2009|p=97}}\n\n===Cancellation===\nThe sites of all three new stations were in semi-rural locations and, as had happened elsewhere, it was intended that the opening of the new section of Underground line would stimulate the construction of new residential estates that the stations would then serve. After the war, however, new legislation was introduced with the intention of limiting the continuing expansion of urban areas into the surrounding countryside. This legislation created the [[Metropolitan Green Belt]] around London and the area designated included the area covered by the new Northern line extension. Without the possibility of constructing the new housing estates, the new line had no purpose and the plans for the extension were cancelled in 1950.{{sfn|Beard|2002|p=126}} \n\nDuring the war, the depot buildings were used for the construction of [[Handley Page Halifax|Halifax]] bombers and the land owned by London Underground at Bushey was used for farming. After the abandonment of the extension plans, the depot buildings became [[Aldenham Works|Aldenham Bus Overhaul Works]].\n\nAs a result of the breakup of London Transport Buses and the devolving of maintenance functions to the depots of individual bus companies, the overhaul works ceased operation in 1986. The premises stood derelict until 1997 when it was demolished and replaced with the Centennial Business Park.\n\nFootage of the overhaul works in operation can be seen in the opening scenes of the 1963 film ''[[Summer Holiday (1963 film)|Summer Holiday]]'' starring [[Cliff Richard]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Edgware, Highgate and London Railway]] - LNER branch line taken over by London Underground as part of the Northern Heights project\n\n==Notes and references==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{ref begin}}\n*{{cite book |last=Beard |first=Tony |title=By Tube Beyond Edgware |publisher=Capital Transport |year=2002 |isbn=978-1-85414-246-7 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Horne |first=Mike |title=The Northern Line, An Illustrated History |year=2009 |origyear=1990 |edition=3rd |publisher=Capital Transport |isbn=978-1-85414-326-6 |ref=harv}}\n{{ref end}}\n\n==External links==\n* London Transport Museum Photographic Archive\n** {{ltmcollection|8q/i000078q.jpg|Land Girls working on London Transport farm at Bushey}}\n** {{ltmcollection|cs/i0000ecs.jpg|Bus overhaul works at Aldenham}}\n* [http://www.abandonedstations.org.uk/Northern_Heights_10.html Abandoned Tube Stations - Northern Heights: Edgware - Bushey Heath]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-note|text=Abandoned Northern Heights Extension |wide=yes }}\n{{s-rail|title=LUL}}\n{{s-line|system=LUL|line=Northern|next=Elstree South|type=Northern Heights|type2=South}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{closed london underground stations}}{{Northern line navbox}}\n{{Closed stations Hertfordshire}}\n\n[[Category:Hertsmere]]\n[[Category:Proposed London Underground stations]]\n[[Category:Unbuilt Northern Heights extension stations]]\n[[Category:Charles Holden railway stations]]\n", "name_user": "TheFrog001", "label": "safe", "comment": "rm extra space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bushey_Heath_tube_station"}
{"title_page": "Bridges Street Market", "text_new": "{{Use Hong Kong English|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n[[File:HK BridgesStreetMarket.JPG|right|thumb|Bridges Street Market in 2008.]]\n[[File:HK Sheung Wan \u5fc5\u70c8\u8005\u58eb\u8857\u8857\u5e02 Bridges Street Market interior 02.JPG|thumb|Bridges Street Market interior in 2010.]]\n'''Bridges Street Market''' ({{zh|t=\u5fc5\u5217\u556b\u58eb\u8857\u8857\u5e02}}) is located at No. 2 [[Bridges Street]], at the corner of [[Shing Wong Street]], in [[Sheung Wan]], [[Hong Kong]]. It is a [[Bauhaus]] style market building, originally opened in 1953,<ref>[[Antiquities and Monuments Office]]: [http://www.aab.gov.hk/form/new_items_history.pdf Historic Building Appraisal, Bridges Street Market] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722123254/http://www.aab.gov.hk/form/new_items_history.pdf |date=22 July 2015 }}</ref> and scheduled to be renovated and open in 2018 as a news museum.<ref>[http://the-sun.on.cc/cnt/news/20110427/00407_037.html \u5fc5\u5217\u556b\u58eb\u8857\u5e02\u300c\u5305\u6d69\u65af\u300d\u6d3b\u5316\u91cd\u751f] ''[[The Sun (Hong Kong)|The Sun]]''. 27 April 2011. {{in lang|zh-hk}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= Chou|first=Oliver |date=22 August 2016 |title=Hong Kong's news museum will show history as it happened |url= http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/education-community/article/2007067/hong-kongs-news-museum-will-show-history-it |newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] |access-date= }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nBridges Street Market was partly built on the site of the former American Congregational Mission Preaching House at which Dr. [[Sun Yat-Sen]] was baptised into Christianity in 1883.<ref>[http://www.fso-createhk.hk/accessibility/eng/locations_search_details.cfm?type=1&File_No=01429 Bridges Street Market \u2013 2 Bridges Street, Central]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Film Services Office. Retrieved 23 September 2011.</ref><ref>[[Antiquities and Monuments Office]]: [http://www.amo.gov.hk/en/trails_sheungwan2.php?tid=17 Original Site of the American Congregational Mission Preaching House, 2 Bridges Street].</ref>\n\n==Conservation==\nBridges Street Market is part of the [[Central and Western Heritage Trail]] and the [[Dr Sun Yat-sen Historical Trail]]. It was listed as a [[List of Grade III historic buildings in Hong Kong|Grade III historic building]] in 2011.<ref name=\"new items\">[http://www.aab.gov.hk/form/list_new_items_assessed.pdf New items in addition to 1,444 historic buildings already assessed] (as of 18 April 2016)</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Hong Kong News-Expo]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{commons category|Bridges Street Market}}\n\n{{Markets in Hong Kong}}\n[[Category:Sheung Wan]]\n[[Category:Retail markets in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Grade III historic buildings in Hong Kong]]\n\n{{coord|22.283324|114.150959|display=title}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use Hong Kong English|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n[[File:HK BridgesStreetMarket.JPG|right|thumb|Bridges Street Market in 2008.]]\n[[File:HK Sheung Wan \u5fc5\u70c8\u8005\u58eb\u8857\u8857\u5e02 Bridges Street Market interior 02.JPG|thumb|Bridges Street Market interior in 2010]]\n'''Bridges Street Market''' ({{zh|t=\u5fc5\u5217\u556b\u58eb\u8857\u8857\u5e02}}) is located at No. 2 [[Bridges Street]], at the corner of [[Shing Wong Street]], in [[Sheung Wan]], [[Hong Kong]]. It is a [[Bauhaus]] style market building, originally opened in 1953,<ref>[[Antiquities and Monuments Office]]: [http://www.aab.gov.hk/form/new_items_history.pdf Historic Building Appraisal, Bridges Street Market] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722123254/http://www.aab.gov.hk/form/new_items_history.pdf |date=22 July 2015 }}</ref> and scheduled to be renovated and open in 2018 as a news museum.<ref>[http://the-sun.on.cc/cnt/news/20110427/00407_037.html \u5fc5\u5217\u556b\u58eb\u8857\u5e02\u300c\u5305\u6d69\u65af\u300d\u6d3b\u5316\u91cd\u751f] ''[[The Sun (Hong Kong)|The Sun]]''. 27 April 2011. {{in lang|zh-hk}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= Chou|first=Oliver |date=22 August 2016 |title=Hong Kong's news museum will show history as it happened |url= http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/education-community/article/2007067/hong-kongs-news-museum-will-show-history-it |newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] |access-date= }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nBridges Street Market was partly built on the site of the former American Congregational Mission Preaching House at which Dr. [[Sun Yat-Sen]] was baptised into Christianity in 1883.<ref>[http://www.fso-createhk.hk/accessibility/eng/locations_search_details.cfm?type=1&File_No=01429 Bridges Street Market \u2013 2 Bridges Street, Central]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Film Services Office. Retrieved 23 September 2011.</ref><ref>[[Antiquities and Monuments Office]]: [http://www.amo.gov.hk/en/trails_sheungwan2.php?tid=17 Original Site of the American Congregational Mission Preaching House, 2 Bridges Street].</ref>\n\n==Conservation==\nBridges Street Market is part of the [[Central and Western Heritage Trail]] and the [[Dr Sun Yat-sen Historical Trail]]. It was listed as a [[List of Grade III historic buildings in Hong Kong|Grade III historic building]] in 2011.<ref name=\"new items\">[http://www.aab.gov.hk/form/list_new_items_assessed.pdf New items in addition to 1,444 historic buildings already assessed] (as of 18 April 2016)</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Hong Kong News-Expo]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{commons category|Bridges Street Market}}\n\n{{Markets in Hong Kong}}\n[[Category:Sheung Wan]]\n[[Category:Retail markets in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Grade III historic buildings in Hong Kong]]\n\n{{coord|22.283324|114.150959|display=title}}\n", "name_user": "Underwaterbuffalo", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bridges_Street_Market"}
{"title_page": "Bronnen (Achstetten)", "text_new": "{{Infobox German location\n|name = Bronnen\n|type = Ortsteil\n|image_photo = Bronnen (Achstetten) Landesarchiv Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg, Abt. Staatsarchiv Sigmaringen N 1-96 T 1 Nr. 246.jpg\n|image_caption = Bronnen\n|image_coa = Wappen Bronnen.png\n|Municipality = Achstetten\n|state = Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg\n|region = T\u00fcbingen\n|district = Biberach\n|coordinates = {{coord|48|14|45|N|9|54|22|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation = 507\n|population = 680\n|Stand = 31-12-2018<ref>[https://www.Achstetten.de/index.php?id=91 Achstetten municipality website]</ref>\n|area_code = 07392\n|postal_code = 88480\n| _noautocat = \n}}\n'''Bronnen''' is a village in the state of [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]], [[Germany]], with a population of 680. Administratively it is part of the municipality of [[Achstetten]].\n\n== Geography ==\nBronnen is located 1 km south of Achstetten, being separated from it by the federal road [[Bundesstra\u00dfe 30]] and 2 km northeast of [[Laupheim]] on the [[Kreisstra\u00dfe|district road]] 7519 The village borders the municipality of [[Burgrieden]] to the southeast. Bronnen is situated on a high [[plateau]] with some built-up area along the main road winding down the slope into the valley of the river [[Rot (Danube)|Rot]]. In Bronnen there are numerous [[well]]s, hence the name of the village which is derived from the [[Old High German]] words ''brunno'' meaning well.\n\n== History ==\nThe area of Bronnen has been settled from early times on. A number of [[Alemanni|Alemannic]] [[Grave field#Alemannic grave fields|grave fields]] have been discovered within its boundaries.<ref name=\"Beck\">{{Cite book  | last = Beck  | first = Otto  | authorlink =   | coauthors =   | title = Kunst und Geschichte im Landkreis Biberach. Ein Reisef\u00fchrer zu Kulturst\u00e4tten und Sehensw\u00fcrdigkeiten in der Mitte Oberschwabens  | publisher = Thorbecke  | year = 1983  | location = Sigmaringen  | pages = 73  | url =   | doi =   | id =   | isbn = 3-7995-3707-4|language=de}}</ref> Bronnen itself was first mentioned as ''Brunnon'' in a document from 8 June 1157 in which a church in the village belonging to [[Saint Blaise Abbey, Black Forest|Saint Blaise Abbey]] is referred to. Bronnen seems to have had its own noble family since between 1265  and 1365 the lords of Bronnen appear in documents, the last one a [[knight]] Brun von Bronnen.<ref name=\"Oberamt\">{{cite book|editor=K\u00f6niglich Statistisch-Topographisches Bureau (W\u00fcrttemberg)|title=Beschreibung des Oberamts Laupheim|publisher=Hallberger |  |date=1856|location=Stuttgart|pages=137ff.|url= |isbn = |language=de}}</ref> From the end of the 14th century until 1639 Bronnen belonged to the lords of Freyberg zu Achstetten.<ref name=\"Leo\">{{cite web | url = https://www.leo-bw.de/web/guest/detail-gis/-/Detail/details/ORT/labw_ortslexikon/17029/Bronnen  | title = Bronnen - Altgemeinde~Teilort |last= |first=   |author-link= | date  =  | publisher  = State of [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]] | language = German | page  = | format =  | accessdate = 19 February 2019}}</ref> [[High, middle and low justice#High justice|High justice]] was executed by the [[Bailiwick]] of Swabia whereas low justice was in the hands of the lords of Freyberg from 1603 onwards. Following the death of the last lord, Philipp Eduard von Freyberg zu Achstetten, the village was after some legal disputes inherited by his four sisters whose heirs eventually sold it to [[Wiblingen Abbey]] in 1710. Low justice passed on first to [[Gutenzell Abbey]] in 1685 and, in 1769, to Wiblingen Abbey.<ref name=\"Beck\" />\n\nDuring the course of the [[German mediatisation]] and the dissolution of Wiblingen Abbey, the village became part of the [[Electorate of Bavaria]] in 1805, and following the establishing of the [[Confederation of the Rhine]] in 1806 it was incorporated into the [[Kingdom of W\u00fcrttemberg]].<ref name=\"Ortsteil\">{{cite web | url = https://achstetten.de/index.php/de/gemeinde/ortsteil-bronnen  | title = Ortsteil Bronnen|last= |first=   |author-link= | date  =  | publisher  = Gemeinde Achstetten | language = German | page  = | format =  | accessdate = 18 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nWith the opening of the [[Laupheim\u2013Schwendi railway]] line in 1904, Bronnen was connected by public transport to [[Schwendi, Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|Schwendi]] and Laupheim.\n\nOn 1 November 1972 Bronnen was joined with the municipality of Achstetten.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://achstetten.de/index.php/de/gemeinde/ortsteil-achstetten   | title = Ortsteil Achstetten |last= |first=   |author-link= | date  =  | publisher  = Gemeinde Achstetten | language = German | page  = | format =  | accessdate = 19 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Coat of arms ==\nThe coat of arms of Bronnen is parted per fess (horizontally) depicting in the upper division a burning golden candle and a golden [[crosier]] on [[Azure (heraldry)|azure]], the [[candle]] being an attribute of [[Saint Blaise|St Blaise]] while the crozier represents the various [[monastery|monasteries]] under whose jurisdictions Bronnen fell or which had certain rights within the village. The lower division shows a village well on [[Or (heraldry)|or]], the well being [[canting arms]] representing the name Bronnen. The [[Tincture (heraldry)|tinctures]] azure and or were taken from the coat of arms of Saint Blaise Abbey to which the church of Bronnen had been affiliated.<ref name=\"Ortsteil\" />\n\n== Economy ==\nUntil the mid-20th century Bronnen was predominantly agrarian-oriented. Today the largest single employer is Erwin Halder KG with approximately 200 employees, manufacturing metal parts and components.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.halder.com/de/UNTERNEHMEN/Ueber-uns  | title = \u00dcber uns |first=   |author-link= | date  =  | publisher  = Erwin Halder KG | language = German | page  = | format =  | accessdate = 19 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Attractions ==\n[[File:Bronnen, parish church St Blaise and Margaret.jpg|thumb|Parish church St Blaise and Margaret in Bronnen]]\n=== Parish church Saint Blaise and Margaret ===\nA church in Bronnen was first mentioned in the 12th century. In 1520 it was dedicated to [[Margaret the Virgin|St Margaret]] and in 1584 also to [[Saint Blaise|St Blaise]].<ref name=\"Leo\" /> The core of the current building is Late [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] but was converted to [[Baroque|Baroque style]] in the 17th and 18th century. In 1658 a tower was added, followed by new [[panelling]] in 1667, and [[Apostle]] figures in 1672. The interior was further reshaped in Baroque and [[Rococo]] styles between 1711 and 1721 and again between 1731 and 1737<ref name=\"Ortsteil\" />  with contributions by [[Painting|painter]] Martin Weller from [[Ehingen]] and [[Sculpture|sculptor]] Dominikus Hermenegild Herberger from [[Dietenheim]] who created a [[processional cross]] and statues of the St Blaise and St Margaret. Between 1869 and 1868 the church's interior was redesigned<ref name=\"Beck\" /> in [[Romanesque Revival architecture|Neo-Romanesque]] style during which most of the Baroque and Rococo interiors were removed. In 1933 the [[nave]] was extended and a [[sacristy]] was added. In 1997 and 1998 the whole structure was renovated.<ref name=\"Ortsteil\" />\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Upper Swabia]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite book| last = | first  = | authorlink = | coauthors  = | title = 850 Jahre Bronnen. 1157 - 2007 | publisher  = Gemeinde Achstetten| year = 2007| location = Achstetten| pages  = | url   = | doi   = | id   = }}\n*{{Cite book  | last = Beck  | first = Otto  | authorlink =   | coauthors =   | title = Kunst und Geschichte im Landkreis Biberach. Ein Reisef\u00fchrer zu Kulturst\u00e4tten und Sehensw\u00fcrdigkeiten in der Mitte Oberschwabens  | publisher = Thorbecke  | year = 1983  | location = Sigmaringen  | pages =   | url =   | doi =   | id =   | isbn = 3-7995-3707-4|language=de}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Bronnen (Achstetten)|Bronnen}}\n*[http://www.achstetten.de Webpage of the municipality of Achstetten (in German)]\n\n[[Category:Achstetten]]\n[[Category:Villages in Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]]\n\n{{improve categories|date=February 2019}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox German location\n|name = Bronnen\n|Type = Ortsteil\n|image_photo = Bronnen (Achstetten) Landesarchiv Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg, Abt. Staatsarchiv Sigmaringen N 1-96 T 1 Nr. 246.jpg\n|image_caption = Bronnen\n|image_coa = Wappen Bronnen.png\n|Municipality = Achstetten\n|state = Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg\n|region = T\u00fcbingen\n|district = Biberach\n|coordinates = {{coord|48|14|45|N|9|54|22|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation = 507\n|population = 680\n|Stand = 31-12-2018<ref>[https://www.Achstetten.de/index.php?id=91 Achstetten municipality website]</ref>\n|area_code = 07392\n|postal_code = 88480\n| _noautocat = \n}}\n'''Bronnen''' is a village in the state of [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]], [[Germany]], with a population of 680. Administratively it is part of the municipality of [[Achstetten]].\n\n== Geography ==\nBronnen is located 1 km south of Achstetten, being separated from it by the federal road [[Bundesstra\u00dfe 30]] and 2 km northeast of [[Laupheim]] on the [[Kreisstra\u00dfe|district road]] 7519 The village borders the municipality of [[Burgrieden]] to the southeast. Bronnen is situated on a high [[plateau]] with some built-up area along the main road winding down the slope into the valley of the river [[Rot (Danube)|Rot]]. In Bronnen there are numerous [[well]]s, hence the name of the village which is derived from the [[Old High German]] words ''brunno'' meaning well.\n\n== History ==\nThe area of Bronnen has been settled from early times on. A number of [[Alemanni|Alemannic]] [[Grave field#Alemannic grave fields|grave fields]] have been discovered within its boundaries.<ref name=\"Beck\">{{Cite book  | last = Beck  | first = Otto  | authorlink =   | coauthors =   | title = Kunst und Geschichte im Landkreis Biberach. Ein Reisef\u00fchrer zu Kulturst\u00e4tten und Sehensw\u00fcrdigkeiten in der Mitte Oberschwabens  | publisher = Thorbecke  | year = 1983  | location = Sigmaringen  | pages = 73  | url =   | doi =   | id =   | isbn = 3-7995-3707-4|language=de}}</ref> Bronnen itself was first mentioned as ''Brunnon'' in a document from 8 June 1157 in which a church in the village belonging to [[Saint Blaise Abbey, Black Forest|Saint Blaise Abbey]] is referred to. Bronnen seems to have had its own noble family since between 1265  and 1365 the lords of Bronnen appear in documents, the last one a [[knight]] Brun von Bronnen.<ref name=\"Oberamt\">{{cite book|editor=K\u00f6niglich Statistisch-Topographisches Bureau (W\u00fcrttemberg)|title=Beschreibung des Oberamts Laupheim|publisher=Hallberger |  |date=1856|location=Stuttgart|pages=137ff.|url= |isbn = |language=de}}</ref> From the end of the 14th century until 1639 Bronnen belonged to the lords of Freyberg zu Achstetten.<ref name=\"Leo\">{{cite web | url = https://www.leo-bw.de/web/guest/detail-gis/-/Detail/details/ORT/labw_ortslexikon/17029/Bronnen  | title = Bronnen - Altgemeinde~Teilort |last= |first=   |author-link= | date  =  | publisher  = State of [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]] | language = German | page  = | format =  | accessdate = 19 February 2019}}</ref> [[High, middle and low justice#High justice|High justice]] was executed by the [[Bailiwick]] of Swabia whereas low justice was in the hands of the lords of Freyberg from 1603 onwards. Following the death of the last lord, Philipp Eduard von Freyberg zu Achstetten, the village was after some legal disputes inherited by his four sisters whose heirs eventually sold it to [[Wiblingen Abbey]] in 1710. Low justice passed on first to [[Gutenzell Abbey]] in 1685 and, in 1769, to Wiblingen Abbey.<ref name=\"Beck\" />\n\nDuring the course of the [[German mediatisation]] and the dissolution of Wiblingen Abbey, the village became part of the [[Electorate of Bavaria]] in 1805, and following the establishing of the [[Confederation of the Rhine]] in 1806 it was incorporated into the [[Kingdom of W\u00fcrttemberg]].<ref name=\"Ortsteil\">{{cite web | url = https://achstetten.de/index.php/de/gemeinde/ortsteil-bronnen  | title = Ortsteil Bronnen|last= |first=   |author-link= | date  =  | publisher  = Gemeinde Achstetten | language = German | page  = | format =  | accessdate = 18 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nWith the opening of the [[Laupheim\u2013Schwendi railway]] line in 1904, Bronnen was connected by public transport to [[Schwendi, Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|Schwendi]] and Laupheim.\n\nOn 1 November 1972 Bronnen was joined with the municipality of Achstetten.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://achstetten.de/index.php/de/gemeinde/ortsteil-achstetten   | title = Ortsteil Achstetten |last= |first=   |author-link= | date  =  | publisher  = Gemeinde Achstetten | language = German | page  = | format =  | accessdate = 19 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Coat of arms ==\nThe coat of arms of Bronnen is parted per fess (horizontally) depicting in the upper division a burning golden candle and a golden [[crosier]] on [[Azure (heraldry)|azure]], the [[candle]] being an attribute of [[Saint Blaise|St Blaise]] while the crozier represents the various [[monastery|monasteries]] under whose jurisdictions Bronnen fell or which had certain rights within the village. The lower division shows a village well on [[Or (heraldry)|or]], the well being [[canting arms]] representing the name Bronnen. The [[Tincture (heraldry)|tinctures]] azure and or were taken from the coat of arms of Saint Blaise Abbey to which the church of Bronnen had been affiliated.<ref name=\"Ortsteil\" />\n\n== Economy ==\nUntil the mid-20th century Bronnen was predominantly agrarian-oriented. Today the largest single employer is Erwin Halder KG with approximately 200 employees, manufacturing metal parts and components.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.halder.com/de/UNTERNEHMEN/Ueber-uns  | title = \u00dcber uns |first=   |author-link= | date  =  | publisher  = Erwin Halder KG | language = German | page  = | format =  | accessdate = 19 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Attractions ==\n[[File:Bronnen, parish church St Blaise and Margaret.jpg|thumb|Parish church St Blaise and Margaret in Bronnen]]\n=== Parish church Saint Blaise and Margaret ===\nA church in Bronnen was first mentioned in the 12th century. In 1520 it was dedicated to [[Margaret the Virgin|St Margaret]] and in 1584 also to [[Saint Blaise|St Blaise]].<ref name=\"Leo\" /> The core of the current building is Late [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] but was converted to [[Baroque|Baroque style]] in the 17th and 18th century. In 1658 a tower was added, followed by new [[panelling]] in 1667, and [[Apostle]] figures in 1672. The interior was further reshaped in Baroque and [[Rococo]] styles between 1711 and 1721 and again between 1731 and 1737<ref name=\"Ortsteil\" />  with contributions by [[Painting|painter]] Martin Weller from [[Ehingen]] and [[Sculpture|sculptor]] Dominikus Hermenegild Herberger from [[Dietenheim]] who created a [[processional cross]] and statues of the St Blaise and St Margaret. Between 1869 and 1868 the church's interior was redesigned<ref name=\"Beck\" /> in [[Romanesque Revival architecture|Neo-Romanesque]] style during which most of the Baroque and Rococo interiors were removed. In 1933 the [[nave]] was extended and a [[sacristy]] was added. In 1997 and 1998 the whole structure was renovated.<ref name=\"Ortsteil\" />\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Upper Swabia]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite book| last = | first  = | authorlink = | coauthors  = | title = 850 Jahre Bronnen. 1157 - 2007 | publisher  = Gemeinde Achstetten| year = 2007| location = Achstetten| pages  = | url   = | doi   = | id   = }}\n*{{Cite book  | last = Beck  | first = Otto  | authorlink =   | coauthors =   | title = Kunst und Geschichte im Landkreis Biberach. Ein Reisef\u00fchrer zu Kulturst\u00e4tten und Sehensw\u00fcrdigkeiten in der Mitte Oberschwabens  | publisher = Thorbecke  | year = 1983  | location = Sigmaringen  | pages =   | url =   | doi =   | id =   | isbn = 3-7995-3707-4|language=de}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Bronnen (Achstetten)|Bronnen}}\n*[http://www.achstetten.de Webpage of the municipality of Achstetten (in German)]\n\n[[Category:Achstetten]]\n[[Category:Villages in Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]]\n\n{{improve categories|date=February 2019}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bronnen_(Achstetten)"}
